nteraction.We use one example of a Russian regulatory measure − the ban on crop residue burning − to explore and systematize critical socio-economic, administrative and institutional factors that diminish the impact of such a command-and-control regulation. Credible monitoring and sanctioning to implement the ban turned out to be almost impossible. Farmers’ beliefs about the positive effects of burning on the soil could not be changed by short-term administrative regulations, and there are no alternative off-field uses for the residue. This empirical study shows that information provision and subsidies for voluntary conservation tillage practices are likely to be more effective measures to counter soil degradation than the residue-burning ban.";s:11:"article_ref";s:67:"https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0264837717300753";s:18:"article_viewscount";s:3:"175";s:17:"article_timestamp";s:19:"2018-05-06 20:34:51";s:14:"article_status";s:1:"1";}i:23;O:8:"stdClass":10:{s:10:"article_id";s:3:"221";s:13:"article_title";s:127:"A longitudinal study of the links between Local Air Quality Management and Local Transport Planning policy processes in England";s:14:"article_author";s:88:"Olowoporoku, A. O.
